$$ N=B/sr^m $$

$$ \ln(sr)=\ln(B/N)^{1/m} \newline \therefore sr=\exp(B/N^{1/m}) $$

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def get_curve(N,B=1e10,m=20):
    return np.exp((B/N)**(1/m))

B=1e10
m=18

xmin=1e0
xmax=12
N=np.logspace(xmin,xmax) # 10^0, 10^10
sr=get_curve(N=N,B=B,m=m)
fig=plt.figure(figsize=(7,2))
ax1=fig.add_subplot(121)
ax2=fig.add_subplot(122)
ax1.plot(N,sr,'-',label='actual')
ax2.plot(N,sr,'-',label='actual')

$$ \dot\varepsilon=K\sigma^n $$ $$ \log(\dot\varepsilon)=\log(K)+n\log(\sigma) $$ $$ \log(\dot\varepsilon)/n-\log(K)/n=\log(\sigma) $$

$$ \log(\dot\varepsilon^{1/n})-\log(K^{1/n})=\log(\sigma) $$

$$ \log((\dot\varepsilon/K)^{1/n})=\log(\sigma) $$

$$ \sigma=(\dot\varepsilon/K)^{1/n} $$

def power(edot,K,n):
    return (edot/K)**(1/n)
def power_tilde(edot,K,n):
    K_std=K/2.
    K_tilde=np.random.normal(0,K_std,size=len(edot))
    n_std=n/10
    n_tilde=np.random.normal(0,n_std,size=len(edot))

    K=K+K_tilde
    n=n+n_tilde
    return (edot/K)**(1/n)

xlows=[-6,-2,2]
xhighs=[-2,3,10]
fig=plt.figure(figsize=(7,3))
ax1=fig.add_subplot(121)
ax2=fig.add_subplot(122)

Ks=[50,0.5,0.2]
ns=[20,10,5]
nsamples=np.array([9,10],dtype='int')
data=np.zeros((2,nsamples.sum()))
i0=0
i1=0
for i in range(2):
    xlow=xlows[i]
    xhigh=xhighs[i]
    edots=np.logspace(xlow,xhigh,nsamples[i])
    K=Ks[i]
    n=ns[i]
    sigma=power(edots,K,n)
    sigma_tilde=power_tilde(edots,K,n)

    i1=i1+nsamples[i]
    data[0,i0:i1]=edots[::]
    data[1,i0:i1]=sigma_tilde[::]

    i0=i0+nsamples[i]

    ax1.plot(edots,sigma,'-')
    ax2.plot(edots,sigma,'-')
    ax1.plot(edots,sigma_tilde,'x')
    ax2.plot(edots,sigma_tilde,'x')

ax1.set_xscale('log')
ax1.set_yscale('log')

np.savetxt('creep.txt',data.T,fmt='%.10e',header='edot, sigma')

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.interpolate import griddata

# -----------------------------
# 1. 실험 데이터 (불연속 측정값)
# -----------------------------
Cu = np.array([2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 15, 18])    # wt% Cu
Temp = np.array([200, 250, 300, 350, 400, 450, 500])  # Heat treatment temp (°C)

# 데이터 포인트 생성 (임의의 실험 결과값)
Cu_data, Temp_data = np.meshgrid(Cu, Temp)
Strength_data = 200 + 5*Cu_data - 0.15*Temp_data + 10*np.sin(Cu_data/3)

# 불규칙한 (x,y,z) 데이터로 변환
x = Cu_data.flatten()
y = Temp_data.flatten()
z = Strength_data.flatten()

# -----------------------------
# 2. 격자(grid) 생성 + 보간
# -----------------------------
grid_x, grid_y = np.meshgrid(
    np.linspace(min(x), max(x), 100),
    np.linspace(min(y), max(y), 100)
)

grid_z = griddata((x, y), z, (grid_x, grid_y), method='cubic')

# -----------------------------
# 3. Contour plot
# -----------------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(7,6))
contours = plt.contour(grid_x, grid_y, grid_z, levels=15, colors='black')
plt.clabel(contours, inline=True, fontsize=8)

plt.contourf(grid_x, grid_y, grid_z, levels=15, cmap='plasma')
plt.scatter(x, y, c=z, cmap='plasma', edgecolor='k')  # 원래 측정점 표시

plt.colorbar(label="Tensile Strength [MPa]")
plt.xlabel("Cu content [%]")
plt.ylabel("Heat treatment Temperature [°C]")
plt.title("Discrete Data → Contour Map (Al-Cu Tensile Strength)")
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.interpolate import griddata

# -----------------------------
# 1. Discrete measurement data
# -----------------------------
points = np.array([
    [0, 0], [0, 1], [0, 2],
    [1, 0], [1, 2],
    [2, 0], [2, 1], [2, 2]
])
values = np.array([30, 35, 32, 40, 38, 45, 44, 42])  # Temperature at points

# -----------------------------
# 2. Interpolation to grid
# -----------------------------
grid_x, grid_y = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(0, 2, 100), np.linspace(0, 2, 100))
grid_z = griddata(points, values, (grid_x, grid_y), method='cubic')

# -----------------------------
# 3. Contour plot
# -----------------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(6,5))
contours = plt.contour(grid_x, grid_y, grid_z, levels=10, colors='black')
plt.clabel(contours, inline=True, fontsize=8)

plt.contourf(grid_x, grid_y, grid_z, levels=10, cmap="coolwarm")
plt.scatter(points[:,0], points[:,1], c=values, cmap="coolwarm", edgecolor="k", s=100)

plt.colorbar(label="Temperature [°C]")
plt.xlabel("x position")
plt.ylabel("y position")
plt.title("Temperature Distribution on a Plate (Discrete → Contour)")
plt.show()

help(np.meshgrid)

Help on _ArrayFunctionDispatcher in module numpy:

meshgrid(*xi, copy=True, sparse=False, indexing='xy')
    Return a list of coordinate matrices from coordinate vectors.

    Make N-D coordinate arrays for vectorized evaluations of
    N-D scalar/vector fields over N-D grids, given
    one-dimensional coordinate arrays x1, x2,..., xn.

    .. versionchanged:: 1.9
       1-D and 0-D cases are allowed.

    Parameters
    ----------
    x1, x2,..., xn : array_like
        1-D arrays representing the coordinates of a grid.
    indexing : {'xy', 'ij'}, optional
        Cartesian ('xy', default) or matrix ('ij') indexing of output.
        See Notes for more details.

        .. versionadded:: 1.7.0
    sparse : bool, optional
        If True the shape of the returned coordinate array for dimension *i*
        is reduced from ``(N1, ..., Ni, ... Nn)`` to
        ``(1, ..., 1, Ni, 1, ..., 1)``.  These sparse coordinate grids are
        intended to be use with :ref:`basics.broadcasting`.  When all
        coordinates are used in an expression, broadcasting still leads to a
        fully-dimensonal result array.

        Default is False.

        .. versionadded:: 1.7.0
    copy : bool, optional
        If False, a view into the original arrays are returned in order to
        conserve memory.  Default is True.  Please note that
        ``sparse=False, copy=False`` will likely return non-contiguous
        arrays.  Furthermore, more than one element of a broadcast array
        may refer to a single memory location.  If you need to write to the
        arrays, make copies first.

        .. versionadded:: 1.7.0

    Returns
    -------
    X1, X2,..., XN : list of ndarrays
        For vectors `x1`, `x2`,..., `xn` with lengths ``Ni=len(xi)``,
        returns ``(N1, N2, N3,..., Nn)`` shaped arrays if indexing='ij'
        or ``(N2, N1, N3,..., Nn)`` shaped arrays if indexing='xy'
        with the elements of `xi` repeated to fill the matrix along
        the first dimension for `x1`, the second for `x2` and so on.

    Notes
    -----
    This function supports both indexing conventions through the indexing
    keyword argument.  Giving the string 'ij' returns a meshgrid with
    matrix indexing, while 'xy' returns a meshgrid with Cartesian indexing.
    In the 2-D case with inputs of length M and N, the outputs are of shape
    (N, M) for 'xy' indexing and (M, N) for 'ij' indexing.  In the 3-D case
    with inputs of length M, N and P, outputs are of shape (N, M, P) for
    'xy' indexing and (M, N, P) for 'ij' indexing.  The difference is
    illustrated by the following code snippet::

        xv, yv = np.meshgrid(x, y, indexing='ij')
        for i in range(nx):
            for j in range(ny):
                # treat xv[i,j], yv[i,j]

        xv, yv = np.meshgrid(x, y, indexing='xy')
        for i in range(nx):
            for j in range(ny):
                # treat xv[j,i], yv[j,i]

    In the 1-D and 0-D case, the indexing and sparse keywords have no effect.

    See Also
    --------
    mgrid : Construct a multi-dimensional "meshgrid" using indexing notation.
    ogrid : Construct an open multi-dimensional "meshgrid" using indexing
            notation.
    how-to-index

    Examples
    --------
    >>> nx, ny = (3, 2)
    >>> x = np.linspace(0, 1, nx)
    >>> y = np.linspace(0, 1, ny)
    >>> xv, yv = np.meshgrid(x, y)
    >>> xv
    array([[0. , 0.5, 1. ],
           [0. , 0.5, 1. ]])
    >>> yv
    array([[0.,  0.,  0.],
           [1.,  1.,  1.]])

    The result of `meshgrid` is a coordinate grid:

    >>> import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    >>> plt.plot(xv, yv, marker='o', color='k', linestyle='none')
    >>> plt.show()

    You can create sparse output arrays to save memory and computation time.

    >>> xv, yv = np.meshgrid(x, y, sparse=True)
    >>> xv
    array([[0. ,  0.5,  1. ]])
    >>> yv
    array([[0.],
           [1.]])

    `meshgrid` is very useful to evaluate functions on a grid. If the
    function depends on all coordinates, both dense and sparse outputs can be
    used.

    >>> x = np.linspace(-5, 5, 101)
    >>> y = np.linspace(-5, 5, 101)
    >>> # full coordinate arrays
    >>> xx, yy = np.meshgrid(x, y)
    >>> zz = np.sqrt(xx**2 + yy**2)
    >>> xx.shape, yy.shape, zz.shape
    ((101, 101), (101, 101), (101, 101))
    >>> # sparse coordinate arrays
    >>> xs, ys = np.meshgrid(x, y, sparse=True)
    >>> zs = np.sqrt(xs**2 + ys**2)
    >>> xs.shape, ys.shape, zs.shape
    ((1, 101), (101, 1), (101, 101))
    >>> np.array_equal(zz, zs)
    True

    >>> h = plt.contourf(x, y, zs)
    >>> plt.axis('scaled')
    >>> plt.colorbar()
    >>> plt.show()
